Dear Hiring Team, 

It is with great pleasure that I submit my candidacy for the Software Engineer position with SeatGeek. I bring over three years of professional experience in full-stack web applications, AI systems, and scalable backend architecture, along with a strong academic foundation as a Master of Science in Computer Science graduate from Pace University, NY.

Through my experience across two engineering roles, I have built and delivered production-grade systems that directly reflect the technical depth and product mindset this position demands. As a Software Engineer at Sperse, I architected a containerized service-oriented architecture for an MCP AI layer that translates natural-language intents into safe, validated tool calls across 1,000+ platform endpoints-requiring rigorous API contract design, input validation, and safe execution across a distributed microservices surface. To keep these systems production-ready, I implemented a robust observability layer using Langfuse, LangSmith, and Datadog-compatible tracing, covering structured logging and evaluation hooks. I optimized high-traffic prompt routing and agent concurrency to maximize KV-cache hit rate, solving complex performance problems that reduced end-to-end latency by 60% and lowered LLM API costs by 50%-the kind of performance optimization and scalability focus that SeatGeek's high-traffic onsales and interactive venue maps demand. Prior to Sperse, as a Software Engineer at Qualitest, I contributed to infrastructure that thousands of users rely on daily. I designed and shipped a cloud-agnostic Storage Service using Python, FastAPI, PostgreSQL, and Redis that seamlessly handled file operations across AWS S3, Google Cloud Storage, and MinIO via expiring signed URLs-giving me direct, hands-on experience with cloud-native, multi-environment backend design. I also contributed to a scalable Identity & Access Management platform built with React, TypeScript, Spring Boot, and AWS, supporting thousands of users across 30+ applications with a product mindset focused on user experience and business impact. Together, these roles have prepared me to ship code to production many times a day, solve complex technical challenges, and contribute meaningfully to SeatGeek's core engineering responsibilities.

My academic research experience has given me a rigorous foundation in model development, GPU-accelerated computing, and technical communication-skills that translate directly into the software craftsmanship and collaborative culture SeatGeek values. As an AI Researcher at the Pace Artificial Intelligence Lab, I conducted applied research on StyleGAN and Stable Diffusion to generate industry-standard fashion designs, leveraging CUDA, PyTorch, and LoRA on Pace University's HPC cluster for model training and fine-tuning. I was responsible for managing the full model development lifecycle-from data preparation and training runs to inference optimization using vLLM and deployment via Hugging Face-ensuring both performance and secure, efficient model serving. Beyond building the systems myself, I led workshops on GPU programming with CUDA and Mojo, and on building AI Agents with LangChain and LangGraph, for an audience of 50+ students. Designing and delivering those sessions required me to break down complex technical concepts clearly and accessibly-directly mirroring the mentoring and knowledge-sharing responsibilities central to this role. This experience has shaped me into an engineer who builds with rigor and communicates with clarity, both of which I would bring to SeatGeek's team.

I have always been passionate about making live events more accessible through transparent, fan-first technology and envision myself contributing my talent to the furthering of SeatGeek's mission to help fans see more live. I would love to discuss my interest in this position with your team and can be reached at #ph or #eml. Thank you for your time and consideration, I look forward to connecting!

